%S A394353 0,1,3,5,6,11,13,18,22,27,30,41,42,57,62,70,74,89,93,115,122,134,143,
%T A394353 169,174,192,200,215,224,252,254,284,292,308,319,345,356,386,401,422,
%U A394353 433,478,489,532,545,562,577,620,627,661,675,707,730,779,787,825,840,872,890,936,944,1004
%N A394353 Number of distinct primes of the form x*y + x*z + y*z with integers 0 <= x <= y <= z <= n.
%C A394353 a(n) > pi(n), since every prime p <= n could be represented as p = 0*1 + 0*p + 1*p, while an additional prime q = 2*m + 1 > n (that exists between n and 2*n by Bertrand's postulate) could be represented as q = 1*1 + 1*m + 1*m with m <= n.
%C A394353 It appears that n*log(n) < a(n) < n^2/2, n > 3.
%e A394353 a(2) = 3, as 2, 3, 5 are represented by triples (0,1,2), (1,1,1), (1,1,2), respectively.
%Y A394353 Cf. A225268 (not restricted to primes).
%K A394353 nonn,new
%O A394353 0,3
